“Lend yourself to others,
but give yourself to yourself.”
— Montaigne

7
00:03:01,181 --> 00:03:08,053
A CAFE — NANA WANTS TO GIVE UP —
PAUL — THE PINBALL MACHINE

8
00:03:12,567 --> 00:03:14,683
Do you really like the guy?

9
00:03:16,113 --> 00:03:18,024
I don’t know.

10
00:03:18,490 --> 00:03:20,526
I wonder
what I was even thinking.

11
00:03:20,701 --> 00:03:22,612
Does he have more money
than me?

12
00:03:22,786 --> 00:03:24,697
What do you care?

13
00:03:25,872 --> 00:03:27,737
What do you care?

14
00:03:34,297 --> 00:03:35,958
Something bothering you?

15
00:03:36,133 --> 00:03:40,126
No, I just wanted to deliver
that line a specific way.

16
00:03:40,595 --> 00:03:43,928
I didn’t know
the best way to say it.

17
00:03:44,307 --> 00:03:48,141
Or I did know,
but I don’t anymore.

18
00:03:48,645 --> 00:03:52,979
Just when I should know, too.
Doesn’t that ever happen to you?

19
00:03:53,233 --> 00:03:56,396
Don’t you ever talk
about anything but yourself?

20
00:03:56,945 --> 00:03:58,731
You’re horrible.

21
00:04:00,615 --> 00:04:03,857
I’m not horrible, Nana.
I’m sad.

22
00:04:04,786 --> 00:04:08,244
I’m not sad, Paul.
l’m horrible.

23
00:04:08,749 --> 00:04:11,741
Don’t talk nonsense.
This isn’t a stage.

24
00:04:13,295 --> 00:04:18,255
You never do as | ask, but you
always want me to do what you want.

25
00:04:19,176 --> 00:04:21,758
Anyway, I’m fed up.
I want to die.

26
00:04:21,928 --> 00:04:24,510
- Is that so?
- Yes, that’s so.

27
00:04:24,681 --> 00:04:26,672
More nonsense.

28
00:04:27,601 --> 00:04:32,186
lt’s exhausting loving you.
I always have to beg.

29
00:04:33,064 --> 00:04:34,929
I exist too.

30
00:04:35,108 --> 00:04:38,100
You say I’m cruel,
but you’re the cruel one.

31
00:04:48,789 --> 00:04:52,998
Why do you say that? It isn’t true.
You mean Sunday evening?

32
00:04:53,960 --> 00:04:55,541
You know very well when.

33
00:04:55,670 --> 00:04:58,503
I begged you
to introduce me to that man.

34
00:04:58,632 --> 00:05:00,964
You did it on purpose.

35
00:05:01,134 --> 00:05:02,670
Yes, I did.

36
00:05:02,844 --> 00:05:05,005
You’re pathetic.

37
00:05:07,098 --> 00:05:10,306
If we started over,
I’d just cheat on you again.

38
00:05:10,477 --> 00:05:12,138
Don’t say that.

39
00:05:17,317 --> 00:05:18,727
Don’t say that.

40
00:05:18,902 --> 00:05:20,142
It’s true.

41
00:05:20,278 --> 00:05:24,817
I thought it was important
we should meet, but I don’t anymore.

42
00:05:25,534 --> 00:05:28,651
We might have
got together again.

43
00:05:28,829 --> 00:05:31,912
But the more we talk,
the less the words mean.

44
00:05:33,208 --> 00:05:37,326
Anyway, if I make it on the stage,
it won’t be thanks to you.

45
00:05:37,796 --> 00:05:39,878
Acting isn’t everything.

46
00:05:40,048 --> 00:05:42,255
Not you too!
Why do you say that?

47
00:05:42,425 --> 00:05:45,167
If it’s what I want,
why should you mind?

48
00:05:45,345 --> 00:05:48,007
I might be discovered
someday.

49
00:05:58,191 --> 00:06:00,398
Yes, you mustn’t give up.

50
00:06:00,652 --> 00:06:03,018
I haven’t given up music.

51
00:06:03,154 --> 00:06:06,988
Not like your English lessons.
You were never really interested.

52
00:06:07,117 --> 00:06:09,028
I’m not giving up.

53
00:06:09,160 --> 00:06:11,867
In fact, that guy’s going
to take pictures of me.

54
00:06:12,831 --> 00:06:15,072
Maybe I’ll get into the movies.

55
00:06:15,542 --> 00:06:17,498
That’ll be the day.

56
00:06:17,836 --> 00:06:20,202
You’re horrible, Paul.

57
00:06:28,430 --> 00:06:30,716
You’re horrible, Paul.

58
00:06:32,225 --> 00:06:35,308
You really are.
It’s always the same.

59
00:06:35,854 --> 00:06:40,689
You say you love me,
but you don’t consider me special.

60
00:06:41,818 --> 00:06:46,903
I hardly love you anymore,
but I still consider you special.

61
00:06:47,407 --> 00:06:51,525
Why do you say things like that?
I think we’re all the same.

62
00:06:52,287 --> 00:06:55,245
You don’t approve of me
looking for work?

63
00:06:55,582 --> 00:06:58,949
lt suits you even less
than all the rest.

64
00:06:59,127 --> 00:07:02,415
Anyway, you’re leaving me
because I’m poor.

65
00:07:02,589 --> 00:07:05,046
When all’s said and done, maybe.

66
00:07:06,426 --> 00:07:09,213
Have you got the pictures
you mentioned on the phone?

67
00:07:10,639 --> 00:07:14,803
I forgot them. They’ll be ready
at the end of the week.

68
00:07:16,269 --> 00:07:18,976
Is he all right?
Is he eating well?

69
00:07:19,147 --> 00:07:22,514
He had an earache,
but the doctor said it was nothing.

70
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:25,149
What’s your job at Pathé-Marconi?

71
00:07:25,320 --> 00:07:27,276
I sell records.

72
00:07:29,115 --> 00:07:31,231
Can you lend me 2,000 francs?

73
00:07:32,035 --> 00:07:33,946
Out of the question.

74
00:07:35,497 --> 00:07:39,160
Your parents
must be glad I’m gone.

75
00:07:39,334 --> 00:07:40,915
No, they liked you.

76
00:07:41,086 --> 00:07:42,667
I’ll bet.

77
00:07:44,422 --> 00:07:46,378
What’s that look for?

78
00:07:52,263 --> 00:07:54,219
What’s that look for?

79
00:07:54,474 --> 00:07:56,055
Nothing.

80
00:07:56,810 --> 00:07:59,677
Let’s not start quarreling again.

81
00:08:00,981 --> 00:08:02,812
How about a game?

82
00:08:02,983 --> 00:08:04,473
Sure.

83
00:08:09,030 --> 00:08:11,191
Got a coin?
I only have one.

84
00:08:11,366 --> 00:08:12,981
Yes, I do.

85
00:08:34,222 --> 00:08:36,087
You go first.

86
00:08:57,078 --> 00:09:00,946
l’m suddenly thinking of those essays
my dad’s students write.

87
00:09:01,124 --> 00:09:02,534
What about them?

88
00:09:02,709 --> 00:09:06,702
He read us some great ones
last night over dinner.

89
00:09:07,047 --> 00:09:11,336
They’re just kids. They had
to describe their favorite animals.

90
00:09:12,052 --> 00:09:14,839
One little girl of eight
chose a bird.

91
00:09:15,972 --> 00:09:17,712
How did it go?

92
00:09:17,891 --> 00:09:21,008
“A bird is an animal
with an inside and an outside.

93
00:09:21,186 --> 00:09:23,518
Take away the outside
and the inside is left.

94
00:09:23,688 --> 00:09:27,272
Take away the inside
and you see its soul.”

95
00:09:37,911 --> 00:09:45,124
THE RECORD SHOP — 2,000 FRANCS —
NANA LIVES HER LIFE

96
00:09:54,511 --> 00:09:56,593
No, we’re out of that, sir.

97
00:10:02,102 --> 00:10:03,888
What about Judy Garland?

98
00:10:05,772 --> 00:10:07,933
We don’t have her either.

99
00:10:11,027 --> 00:10:15,612
Do you have a guitar recording
by Roméo —

100
00:10:16,616 --> 00:10:19,483
What’s his name?
Rafael Romero.

101
00:10:21,037 --> 00:10:22,527
I’ll ask.

102
00:10:25,875 --> 00:10:28,036
Rafael Romero on guitar.

103
00:10:28,169 --> 00:10:30,535
In the bins in back.

104
00:10:56,990 --> 00:10:58,696
ls Rita still sick?

105
00:10:58,867 --> 00:11:01,483
Yes. I think she’ll be back
Thursday.

106
00:11:01,661 --> 00:11:03,993
What a drag.
She owes me 2,000 francs.

107
00:11:08,293 --> 00:11:11,956
- Can you lend me 2,000?
- You crazy? I’m broke.

108
00:11:12,922 --> 00:11:16,085
Why? Anything wrong?
- No, nothing.

109
00:11:16,259 --> 00:11:17,669
Here it is.

110
00:11:18,428 --> 00:11:20,384
I’ll take this too.

111
00:11:39,657 --> 00:11:41,397
This way, sir.

112
00:12:23,076 --> 00:12:25,032
That looks great.

113
00:12:25,161 --> 00:12:28,949
The story’s stupid,
but it’s very well written.

114
00:12:29,874 --> 00:12:33,458
“He gazed at the turquoise,
star-laden sky

115
00:12:33,628 --> 00:12:35,584
and then turned to me.

116
00:12:35,755 --> 00:12:39,043
‘You live your life intensely,
so logically —’

117
00:12:39,217 --> 00:12:40,707
l interrupted him.

118
00:12:40,885 --> 00:12:43,922
‘You attach
too much importance to logic.’

119
00:12:44,097 --> 00:12:49,137
For a few seconds l was filled
with a bitter sense of triumph.

120
00:12:49,310 --> 00:12:52,928
No more broken heart,
no more struggle to live again.

121
00:12:53,064 --> 00:12:56,977
No probing questions to face
while masking one’s defeat.

122
00:12:57,151 --> 00:13:00,860
Yes, a truly elegant way
of breaking this deadlock.”

123
00:13:09,747 --> 00:13:12,739
THE CONCIERGE — PAUL —

124
00:13:12,917 --> 00:13:16,409
THE PASS/0N 0F JOAN OFAHC —
A JOURNALIST

125
00:13:42,530 --> 00:13:44,566
Please give me my key.

126
00:13:45,992 --> 00:13:47,698
All right, then.

127
00:13:51,664 --> 00:13:53,996
Arthur! Get her!

128
00:13:58,171 --> 00:14:00,378
Come on, give me the key.

129
00:14:06,179 --> 00:14:07,669
Here, honey.

130
00:14:12,477 --> 00:14:13,683
Hi.

131
00:14:14,687 --> 00:14:16,097
Where are you headed?

132
00:14:16,272 --> 00:14:18,263
Want to see the pictures?

133
00:14:26,532 --> 00:14:30,525
He doesn’t look like me at all.
He looks more like you.

134
00:14:31,496 --> 00:14:33,032
Come have dinner?

135
00:14:34,374 --> 00:14:37,582
- Where are you going?
- Boulevard Saint-Michel.

136
00:14:37,710 --> 00:14:40,326
- Come have dinner.
- I’m not hungry.

137
00:14:40,505 --> 00:14:43,167
I want to see a movie.
Bye.

138
00:14:46,969 --> 00:14:49,255
JOAN OF ARC

139
00:15:19,627 --> 00:15:23,711
We have come
to prepare you for death!

140
00:15:37,019 --> 00:15:39,431
Now... already?

141
00:15:49,782 --> 00:15:51,272
How am I to die?

142
00:15:56,330 --> 00:15:57,820
At the stake!

143
00:16:10,928 --> 00:16:15,968
How can you still believe
you were sent by God?

144
00:16:20,855 --> 00:16:26,691
God knows our path, but we understand it
only at the end of the road!

145
00:16:38,039 --> 00:16:40,030
Yes, I am his child!

146
00:16:50,009 --> 00:16:52,000
And the great victory?

147
00:16:59,227 --> 00:17:01,559
It will be my martyrdom!

148
00:17:02,855 --> 00:17:03,844
And your deliverance?

149
00:17:13,991 --> 00:17:15,356
Death!

150
00:17:30,466 --> 00:17:32,252
Death.

151
00:17:41,477 --> 00:17:43,468
I said good-bye already.

152
00:17:43,646 --> 00:17:45,432
I paid for your movie ticket.

153
00:17:45,606 --> 00:17:47,267
Too bad.

154
00:17:56,742 --> 00:17:58,733
Evening. How are you?

155
00:17:58,911 --> 00:18:00,572
Evening. How are things?

156
00:18:00,913 --> 00:18:03,825
- Didn’t we have a date tonight?
- Yes.

157
00:18:04,333 --> 00:18:07,666
I wondered if you were coming.
- Why? Am I late?

158
00:18:07,837 --> 00:18:11,580
Just a bit.
But that’s not why I wondered.

159
00:18:12,008 --> 00:18:14,750
I’m usually very punctual.

160
00:18:16,262 --> 00:18:18,628
11:00 pm. is very late.

161
00:18:23,352 --> 00:18:25,889
I thought you’d forgotten too.

162
00:18:27,148 --> 00:18:28,638
What will you have?

163
00:18:28,816 --> 00:18:31,307
- Any rolls left?
- Sorry, no.

164
00:18:31,485 --> 00:18:33,271
A coffee, then.

165
00:18:35,906 --> 00:18:38,739
Was that a friend outside?

166
00:18:38,993 --> 00:18:41,109
No, it was my brother.

167
00:18:41,829 --> 00:18:43,865
You have lots
of brothers and sisters?

168
00:18:44,040 --> 00:18:46,907
Five brothers and three sisters.

169
00:18:47,585 --> 00:18:50,247
Surprised? It’s true.

170
00:18:52,923 --> 00:18:55,289
What’s new since Wednesday?

171
00:18:55,968 --> 00:18:58,004
Nothing much.

172
00:18:59,013 --> 00:19:01,720
Is that red car outside yours?

173
00:19:02,600 --> 00:19:04,807
What is it? A Jaguar?

174
00:19:04,977 --> 00:19:09,471
No, an Alfa Romeo.
Are you interested in cars?

175
00:19:09,649 --> 00:19:12,812
No, I don’t know
a thing about them.

176
00:19:14,403 --> 00:19:17,816
When shall we take
those pictures?

177
00:19:18,407 --> 00:19:21,991
You tell me.
I already told you I’m ready.

178
00:19:22,536 --> 00:19:24,743
But I’m only free on Sundays.

179
00:19:25,998 --> 00:19:28,614
I’m off to London on Sunday.

180
00:19:28,959 --> 00:19:31,041
Well then, I don’t know.

181
00:19:33,547 --> 00:19:36,835
How about now?
Are you tired?

182
00:19:37,677 --> 00:19:41,386
If I say no,
you won’t think I’m awful?

183
00:19:41,555 --> 00:19:43,591
Not at all.

184
00:19:45,476 --> 00:19:48,593
Do you really think
I could get into films?

185
00:19:48,771 --> 00:19:50,227
I think so.

186
00:19:50,398 --> 00:19:53,515
Look, I brought you
a composite sheet.

187
00:20:03,202 --> 00:20:05,784
I’d like to do
something like that.

188
00:20:07,707 --> 00:20:09,197
What’s this for?

189
00:20:09,375 --> 00:20:12,913
You send it out
to people in films,

190
00:20:13,546 --> 00:20:16,879
and a few days later
maybe they call you.

191
00:20:19,176 --> 00:20:21,838
I’m a bit shy
about undressing.

192
00:20:22,012 --> 00:20:24,594
Just a little.
What can it hurt?

193
00:20:26,767 --> 00:20:29,600
Could you lend me 2,000 francs?

194
00:20:29,770 --> 00:20:32,056
I would, but I haven’t got it.

195
00:20:33,733 --> 00:20:35,519
I’m tired.

196
00:20:40,740 --> 00:20:42,526
What about my pictures?

197
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:45,532
You’ll come with me then?

198
00:21:01,010 --> 00:21:08,928
THE POLICE —
NANA IS QUESTIONED

199
00:21:12,521 --> 00:21:15,354
Nana Klein-what ?

200
00:21:16,317 --> 00:21:21,311
K-L-E-I-N...

201
00:21:22,448 --> 00:21:28,489
F-R-A-N-K-E-N...

202
00:21:28,662 --> 00:21:31,620
H-E-I-M.

203
00:21:33,125 --> 00:21:38,336
Born Apr/7 15th, 7940,
a! F/exburg, Mose/la.

204
00:21:38,506 --> 00:21:41,213
No fixed address.
Is that ﬁght?

205
00:21:41,675 --> 00:21:43,131
Yes.

206
00:21:43,636 --> 00:21:45,797
A// ﬁght. What happened?

207
00:21:46,222 --> 00:21:49,965
Well, I was walking
down the street,

208
00:21:50,142 --> 00:21:53,054
and I saw a woman
buying a magazine.

209
00:21:53,479 --> 00:21:58,564
Then... she took some money
out of her bag.

210
00:21:59,777 --> 00:22:02,985
She didn’t notice
she’d dropped 1,000 francs.

211
00:22:03,948 --> 00:22:09,659
So then... I pretended
to buy a magazine too,

212
00:22:10,120 --> 00:22:13,487
and I put my foot
on her 1,000 francs.

213
00:22:15,584 --> 00:22:18,326
She left and —

214
00:22:24,844 --> 00:22:27,210
And she realized it?

215
00:22:38,190 --> 00:22:40,522
She walked back toward me...

216
00:22:41,569 --> 00:22:44,356
and stared into my eyes
for a long time.

217
00:22:46,198 --> 00:22:50,407
So I gave her back her money.

218
00:22:59,044 --> 00:23:01,376
Then why did she bring charges?

219
00:23:01,839 --> 00:23:05,673
I don’t know.
I think it was very mean of her.

220
00:23:14,351 --> 00:23:17,309
Don’t you have anyone
you can stay with in Paris?

221
00:23:18,355 --> 00:23:20,437
Friends, sometimes.

222
00:23:21,567 --> 00:23:23,273
Boys?

223
00:23:26,280 --> 00:23:28,020
Sometimes.

224
00:23:32,077 --> 00:23:34,693
Why not ask
for an advance at work?

225
00:23:35,831 --> 00:23:38,413
I already have, too many times.

226
00:23:41,086 --> 00:23:43,372
What are you going to do?

227
00:23:43,714 --> 00:23:45,375
I don’t know.

228
00:23:45,633 --> 00:23:47,294


229
00:23:48,427 --> 00:23:50,839
l... is someone else.

230
00:23:56,060 --> 00:24:02,932
THE BOULEVARDS —
THE FIRST MAN — THE ROOM

231
00:25:09,008 --> 00:25:10,714
How about it?

232
00:25:22,563 --> 00:25:24,474
Is this the place?

233
00:25:25,107 --> 00:25:27,223
You’ve been here before?

234
00:25:28,068 --> 00:25:29,899
Yes, it is.

235
00:25:45,878 --> 00:25:47,584
Anyone there?

236
00:25:47,796 --> 00:25:49,878
You want Room 27 or 28?

237
00:25:52,176 --> 00:25:53,541
Room 27.

238
00:27:07,918 --> 00:27:10,455
- Do you smoke?
- No, thanks.

239
00:27:15,926 --> 00:27:17,917
There’s never an ashtray.

240
00:27:19,930 --> 00:27:21,716
Here’s one.

241
00:27:33,944 --> 00:27:35,855
How much do you want?

242
00:27:37,447 --> 00:27:40,154
I don’t know.
It’s up to you.

243
00:27:42,995 --> 00:27:44,860
I don’t know.

244
00:27:46,248 --> 00:27:47,988
Four thousand francs?

245
00:28:05,976 --> 00:28:07,841
You owe me 1,000.

246
00:28:08,020 --> 00:28:09,806
l have no change.

247
00:28:10,731 --> 00:28:13,438
Keep it.
It doesn’t matter.

248
00:28:13,609 --> 00:28:16,567
It’s true.
I’m not just trying to get more.

249
00:28:17,362 --> 00:28:19,728
But you have
to take everything off.

250
00:28:28,665 --> 00:28:30,747
Why not on the mouth?

251
00:28:41,303 --> 00:28:44,591
MEETING YVETTE —
A CAFE IN THE SUBURBS —

252
00:28:44,765 --> 00:28:48,223
RAOUL —
GUNSHOTS IN THE STREET

253
00:29:04,451 --> 00:29:06,487
Yvette! How are you?

254
00:29:06,620 --> 00:29:09,487
Is that you? You cut your hair!
