- How are you?
- So-so.

513
00:52:36,945 --> 00:52:38,481
What’s wrong with her?

514
00:52:38,656 --> 00:52:40,817
We were supposed
to see a movie.

515
00:52:40,991 --> 00:52:42,822
l’ll cheer you up.

516
00:52:52,461 --> 00:52:55,703
I’ll do the kid
blowing up a balloon.

517
00:53:05,015 --> 00:53:08,507
He’s got a balloon,
and he blows it up.

518
00:53:52,730 --> 00:53:55,312
You ought to be my man.

519
00:53:55,566 --> 00:53:57,932
Happy now?
Will you let us talk?

520
00:57:31,949 --> 00:57:40,823
THE STREETS — A GUY —
HAPPINESS IS NO FUN

521
00:58:21,832 --> 00:58:25,074
Did you see Inspector Fleytoux?
He bought a BMW.

522
00:58:57,576 --> 00:58:59,783
They could have provided chairs.

523
00:58:59,953 --> 00:59:02,035
It’s always like that.

524
00:59:09,421 --> 00:59:10,752
How much?

525
00:59:10,922 --> 00:59:13,664
3,000.
5,000 if I undress.

526
00:59:15,635 --> 00:59:19,503
Can’t you give me one more?
- l have to keep some.

527
00:59:20,640 --> 00:59:22,551
- One of these, then?
- It’s all I’ve got.

528
00:59:22,726 --> 00:59:25,638
A little one.
It would be so nice.

529
00:59:28,732 --> 00:59:30,518
You come here often?

530
00:59:32,903 --> 00:59:35,110
But I’ve seen you before,
haventl?

531
00:59:35,322 --> 00:59:36,812
Maybe.

532
00:59:40,077 --> 00:59:42,033
What’s your name?

533
00:59:42,204 --> 00:59:43,819
Dimitri.

534
00:59:45,082 --> 00:59:46,697
Nice name.

535
00:59:49,127 --> 00:59:51,459
Yes, I’m fond of it.

536
00:59:52,089 --> 00:59:54,080
What line of work are you in?

537
00:59:54,257 --> 00:59:57,090
I shoot pictures for ads.

538
00:59:57,260 --> 00:59:59,125
You mean like in the movies?

539
00:59:59,304 --> 01:00:01,260
No, still pictures.

540
01:00:02,099 --> 01:00:05,057
l was in a movie with
Eddie Constantine two months ago.

541
01:00:05,268 --> 01:00:08,135
No Pity.
Did you see it?

542
01:00:12,526 --> 01:00:16,439
You don’t say much.
Are you the romantic type?

543
01:00:22,369 --> 01:00:25,281
If you give me more,
you can stay.

544
01:00:30,669 --> 01:00:32,876
That’s what you want?

545
01:00:34,089 --> 01:00:35,704
I’ll go see.

546
01:00:43,974 --> 01:00:45,589
Never mind.

547
01:00:54,609 --> 01:00:56,645
- Are you leaving?
- Yes.

548
01:00:58,613 --> 01:01:02,481
- Can you spare five minutes?
- Ask Monique. She’s in 41.

549
01:01:15,046 --> 01:01:17,788
- What’s up?
- Nothing.

550
01:01:20,802 --> 01:01:23,009
The elevators never work.

551
01:01:24,472 --> 01:01:27,009
See you Tuesday
at the Olympia.

552
01:01:42,032 --> 01:01:43,818
- What are you doing?
- Going downstairs.

553
01:01:43,992 --> 01:01:46,859
- Can you spare a moment?
- How much?

554
01:01:47,037 --> 01:01:49,653
I don’t know.
We can discuss it.

555
01:01:49,873 --> 01:01:51,329
All right.

556
01:01:51,458 --> 01:01:53,494
Room 45.

557
01:02:14,898 --> 01:02:17,184
Work it out with her.

558
01:02:23,657 --> 01:02:26,148
- All right?
- Yes.

559
01:02:32,082 --> 01:02:35,666
- What’s your name?
- Elizabeth. Like the Queen of England.

560
01:02:38,630 --> 01:02:40,871
Shall I strip too?

561
01:02:41,049 --> 01:02:42,789
Actually, don’t bother.

562
01:02:42,968 --> 01:02:45,209
So you don’t need me anymore?

563
01:02:45,679 --> 01:02:47,340
I don’t know.

564
01:02:56,564 --> 01:02:58,270
Like that.

565
01:03:12,289 --> 01:03:19,286
PLACE DU CHATELET — A STRANGER —
NANA, THE UNWITTING PHILOSOPHER

566
01:04:30,950 --> 01:04:33,362
Do you mind me looking?

567
01:04:36,706 --> 01:04:38,537
You look bored.

568
01:04:38,708 --> 01:04:40,164
Not at all.

569
01:04:42,504 --> 01:04:45,166
- What are you doing?
- Reading.

570
01:04:54,849 --> 01:04:56,805
Will you buy me a drink?

571
01:04:57,560 --> 01:04:59,266
if you l/ke.

572
01:05:06,111 --> 01:05:07,976
Do you come here often?

573
01:05:08,154 --> 01:05:11,146
Occasionally.
Today | just happened by.

574
01:05:12,992 --> 01:05:14,983
Why are you reading?

575
01:05:15,161 --> 01:05:16,822
It’s my job.

576
01:05:22,961 --> 01:05:24,917
It’s funny.

577
01:05:25,046 --> 01:05:27,082
Suddenly I don’t know what to say.

578
01:05:27,966 --> 01:05:30,002
It happens to me a lot.

579
01:05:30,468 --> 01:05:32,504
I know what I want to say.

580
01:05:32,679 --> 01:05:36,888
I think first about whether
they’re the right words.

581
01:05:37,350 --> 01:05:42,219
But when the moment comes
to speak, I can’t say it.

582
01:05:42,397 --> 01:05:44,763
Yes, of course.

583
01:05:45,442 --> 01:05:47,774
Have you read
The Three Musketeers?

584
01:05:47,944 --> 01:05:51,186
No, but I saw the movie. Why?

585
01:05:53,074 --> 01:05:57,283
Because in it, Porthos —

586
01:05:58,288 --> 01:06:01,496
Actually, this is from
Twenty Years Later

587
01:06:01,666 --> 01:06:05,579
Porthos is tall, strong,
and a little dense.

588
01:06:06,588 --> 01:06:09,580
He’s never had a thought in his life.

589
01:06:10,508 --> 01:06:15,798
He has to place a bomb
in a cellar to blow it up.

590
01:06:15,972 --> 01:06:17,883
He does it.

591
01:06:18,057 --> 01:06:22,471
He places the bomb, lights the fuse,
and starts to run away.

592
01:06:23,188 --> 01:06:26,100
But just then he begins to think.

593
01:06:27,317 --> 01:06:29,228
About what?

594
01:06:29,402 --> 01:06:33,486
How it’s possible to put
one foot in front of the other.

595
01:06:33,656 --> 01:06:36,318
I’m sure that’s happened to you.

596
01:06:37,994 --> 01:06:42,408
So he stops running.
He can’t move fonNard.

597
01:06:45,668 --> 01:06:49,160
The bomb explodes,
and the cellar caves in around him.

598
01:06:49,339 --> 01:06:52,502
He holds it up
with his strong shoulders.

599
01:06:52,675 --> 01:06:57,419
But after a day or two,
he’s crushed to death.

600
01:06:58,014 --> 01:07:00,596
So the first time he thought,
it killed him.

601
01:07:00,725 --> 01:07:03,467
Why do you tell me
things like that?

602
01:07:04,312 --> 01:07:07,224
No reason. Just to talk.

603
01:07:07,398 --> 01:07:09,889
Why must one always talk?

604
01:07:10,568 --> 01:07:14,777
I think one should often
just keep quiet, live in silence.

605
01:07:16,074 --> 01:07:19,407
The more one talks,
the less the words mean.

606
01:07:19,577 --> 01:07:22,694
Perhaps,
but can one do that?

607
01:07:24,374 --> 01:07:25,363
I don’t know.

608
01:07:25,542 --> 01:07:29,285
It’s always struck me,
the fact we can’t live without speaking.

609
01:07:34,050 --> 01:07:36,792
But it would be nice.

610
01:07:37,387 --> 01:07:40,720
Yes, it would be nice, wouldn’t it?

611
01:07:41,724 --> 01:07:44,431
Sort of like we loved
one another more.

612
01:07:44,602 --> 01:07:47,719
But it’s impossible.
No one’s been able to.

613
01:07:47,855 --> 01:07:49,391
But why?

614
01:07:49,566 --> 01:07:52,729
Words should express
just what one wants to say.

615
01:07:53,403 --> 01:07:55,064
Do they betray us?

616
01:07:56,906 --> 01:07:59,067
Yes, but we betray them too.

617
01:07:59,242 --> 01:08:01,403
One should be able
to express oneself.

618
01:08:01,578 --> 01:08:03,944
We manage
to write things quite well.

619
01:08:04,122 --> 01:08:07,990
It’s extraordinary
that someone like Plato

620
01:08:08,167 --> 01:08:12,080
can still be understood.
People really do understand him.

621
01:08:12,255 --> 01:08:16,123
Yet he wrote in Greek
2,500 years ago.

622
01:08:16,301 --> 01:08:21,466
No one really knows
the language, not exactly.

623
01:08:21,806 --> 01:08:26,175
Yet something gets through, so we
should be able to express ourselves.

624
01:08:27,729 --> 01:08:29,765
And we have to.

625
01:08:29,939 --> 01:08:33,932
Why do we have to?
To understand each other?

626
01:08:38,615 --> 01:08:40,606
We must think,

627
01:08:41,117 --> 01:08:43,733
and for thought we need words.

628
01:08:43,911 --> 01:08:46,118
There’s no other way to think.

629
01:08:46,289 --> 01:08:49,747
To communicate, one must speak.
That’s our life.

630
01:08:49,917 --> 01:08:52,499
Yes, but at the same time,
it’s very hard.

631
01:08:56,382 --> 01:08:59,624
Whereas I think
life should be easy.

632
01:09:03,306 --> 01:09:07,800
Your tale about the Three Musketeers
may be a very nice story,

633
01:09:08,186 --> 01:09:09,847
but it’s terrible.

634
01:09:10,021 --> 01:09:12,763
Yes, but it’s a pointer.

635
01:09:14,067 --> 01:09:15,807
I believe

636
01:09:16,736 --> 01:09:22,322
one learns to speak well only when
one has renounced life for a while.

637
01:09:22,492 --> 01:09:25,484
That’s the price.
- So to speak is fatal?

638
01:09:25,620 --> 01:09:29,989
Speaking is almost
a resurrection in relation to life.

639
01:09:30,166 --> 01:09:34,330
Speaking is a different life
from when one does not speak.

640
01:09:34,504 --> 01:09:37,792
So to live speaking,

641
01:09:38,341 --> 01:09:41,959
one must pass through
the death of life without speaking.

642
01:09:42,095 --> 01:09:44,962
I don’t know if I’m being clear...

643
01:09:46,516 --> 01:09:51,180
but there’s a kind of ascetic rule
that stops one from speaking well

644
01:09:51,813 --> 01:09:55,021
until one sees life with detachment.

645
01:09:57,360 --> 01:10:03,105
But one can’t live everyday life
with... I don’t know —

646
01:10:04,158 --> 01:10:05,898
Detachment?

647
01:10:06,077 --> 01:10:10,662
We go back and forth. That’s why
we pass from silence to words.

648
01:10:11,249 --> 01:10:16,209
We swing between the two,
because it’s the movement of life.

649
01:10:16,629 --> 01:10:20,713
From everyday life
one rises to a life —

650
01:10:20,883 --> 01:10:25,422
Let’s call it superior — why not?
It’s the thinking life.

651
01:10:25,596 --> 01:10:29,509
But the thinking life presupposes
that one has killed off

652
01:10:29,684 --> 01:10:32,801
a life that’s too mundane,
too rudimentary.

653
01:10:34,647 --> 01:10:38,435
Then thinking and speaking
are the same thing?

654
01:10:38,735 --> 01:10:40,521
I believe so.

655
01:10:40,695 --> 01:10:44,279
It’s in Plato, you know.
It’s an old idea.

656
01:10:44,449 --> 01:10:48,237
I don’t think
one can distinguish a thought

657
01:10:48,411 --> 01:10:50,868
from the words that express it.

658
01:10:50,997 --> 01:10:57,084
A moment of thought can only
be grasped through words.

659
01:10:57,253 --> 01:10:59,869
So to speak is to risk lying?

660
01:11:00,047 --> 01:11:02,959
Lies too are part of our quest.

661
01:11:03,134 --> 01:11:06,422
There’s little difference
between an error and a lie.

662
01:11:06,596 --> 01:11:11,181
I don’t mean ordinary lies,
like promising,

663
01:11:11,350 --> 01:11:15,764
“I’ll be here tomorrow at 5:00,”
and then not showing up.

664
01:11:15,938 --> 01:11:17,974
Those are just ploys.

665
01:11:18,149 --> 01:11:24,486
But a subtle lie
often differs little from an error.

666
01:11:24,655 --> 01:11:28,614
One’s searching for something
and can’t find the right word.

667
01:11:28,785 --> 01:11:33,074
That’s why you didn’t know
what to say before.

668
01:11:33,247 --> 01:11:37,115
I think you were afraid
of not finding the right word.

669
01:11:39,879 --> 01:11:43,371
How can one be sure
of having found the right word?

670
01:11:45,843 --> 01:11:49,552
One must work at it.
It only comes with effort.

671
01:11:49,722 --> 01:11:54,261
To say what must be said
in the appropriate way,

672
01:11:54,393 --> 01:11:56,509
that is, that doesn’t hurt,

673
01:11:56,646 --> 01:12:00,104
that says what must be said,
does what must be done,

674
01:12:00,233 --> 01:12:02,770
without hurting
or wounding anyone.

675
01:12:04,320 --> 01:12:07,608
One must try to act in good faith.

676
01:12:09,075 --> 01:12:10,986
Someone once told me,

677
01:12:11,160 --> 01:12:14,994
“There’s truth in everything,
even in error.”

678
01:12:15,957 --> 01:12:17,242
It’s true.

679
01:12:17,416 --> 01:12:21,329
That’s what France didn’t see
in the 17th century.

680
01:12:21,504 --> 01:12:26,123
They thought one could
avoid errors and lies,

681
01:12:26,300 --> 01:12:29,463
that one could live
directly in the truth.

682
01:12:29,637 --> 01:12:31,343
I don’t think it’s possible.

683
01:12:31,514 --> 01:12:34,631
Hence Kant, Hegel,
German philosophy:

684
01:12:34,809 --> 01:12:37,596
to bring us back to life

685
01:12:37,770 --> 01:12:42,981
and make us see that we must pass
through error to arrive at truth.

686
01:12:46,529 --> 01:12:48,861
What do you think about love?

687
01:12:51,576 --> 01:12:55,239
The body had to come into it,

688
01:12:55,413 --> 01:12:58,155
andindeed,
Leibniz introduced the contingent.

689
01:12:58,332 --> 01:13:02,701
Contingent truths
and necessary truths make up life.

690
01:13:02,879 --> 01:13:06,872
German philosophy
showed us that in life,

691
01:13:07,049 --> 01:13:11,088
one thinks with the constraints
and errors of life.

692
01:13:11,262 --> 01:13:14,550
One must manage with that.
It’s true.

693
01:13:16,684 --> 01:13:20,302
Shouldn’t love be the only truth?

694
01:13:22,231 --> 01:13:26,019
But for that,
love would always have to be true.

695
01:13:26,193 --> 01:13:30,232
Do you know anyone who knows
right off what he loves?

696
01:13:31,365 --> 01:13:34,323
No. When you’re 20,
you don’t know.

697
01:13:34,493 --> 01:13:38,577
All you know are bits and pieces.
You grasp at experience.

698
01:13:38,748 --> 01:13:42,332
At that age, “I love”
is a mixture of many things.

699
01:13:42,501 --> 01:13:48,542
To be completely at one
with what you love takes maturity.

700
01:13:48,716 --> 01:13:50,877
That means searching.

701
01:13:51,052 --> 01:13:53,134
That’s the truth of life.

702
01:13:54,722 --> 01:13:57,259
That’s why love is a solution,

703
01:13:57,433 --> 01:14:00,641
but on the condition that it be true.

704
01:14:02,480 --> 01:14:10,319
THE YOUNG MAN AGAIN — THE OVAL
PORTRAIT — RAOUL TRADES NANA

705
01:14:20,414 --> 01:14:22,279
What shall we do today?

706
01:14:23,084 --> 01:14:24,369
I don’t know.

707
01:14:24,502 --> 01:14:26,788
Shall we go
to the Luxembourg Garden?

708
01:14:29,590 --> 01:14:32,457
I think it’s going to rain.

709
01:14:34,512 --> 01:14:38,755
“/ thus saw in vivid lrght
a picture all unnoticed before.

710
01:14:39,725 --> 01:14:43,934
It was the portrait of a young girl
just ripening into womanhood.

711
01:14:44,146 --> 01:14:48,606
I glanced at the painting hurriedly,
and then closed my eyes.

712
01:14:57,493 --> 01:15:01,361
It was an impulsive movement
to gain time for thought,

713
01:15:02,164 --> 01:15:05,201
to make sure that my vision
had not deceived me,

714
01:15:05,376 --> 01:15:10,336
to calm and subdue my fancy
for a more sober and more certain gaze.

715
01:15:11,007 --> 01:15:15,501
In a very few moments
I again looked fixedly at the painting.

716
01:15:21,726 --> 01:15:25,935
The portrait, l have already said,
was that of a young girl.

717
01:15:27,064 --> 01:15:29,931
It was a mere head and shoulders,

718
01:15:30,109 --> 01:15:34,227
done in what is technically
termed a vignette manner,

719
01:15:34,864 --> 01:15:38,698
much in the style
of the favorite heads of Sully.

720
01:15:38,993 --> 01:15:43,202
The arms, the bosom,
and even the ends of the radiant hair

721
01:15:43,372 --> 01:15:47,456
melted imperceptibly
into the vague yet deep shadow

722
01:15:47,626 --> 01:15:49,912
which formed
the background of the whole.

723
01:15:51,088 --> 01:15:54,171
As a thing of art,
nothing could be more admirable

724
01:15:54,341 --> 01:15:56,582
than the painting itself.

725
01:15:57,261 --> 01:16:00,628
But it could have been
neither the execution of the work,

726
01:16:00,806 --> 01:16:02,888
nor the immortal beauty
of the countenance,

727
01:16:03,059 --> 01:16:06,517
which had so suddenly
and so vehemently moved me.

728
01:16:06,687 --> 01:16:11,056
Least of all could it have been that
my fancy, shaken from its half slumber,

729
01:16:11,233 --> 01:16:14,350
had mistaken the head
for that of a living person.

730
01:16:18,240 --> 01:16:22,324
At length, satisfied
with the true secret of its effect,

731
01:16:22,495 --> 01:16:25,077
I fell back within the bed.

732
01:16:25,247 --> 01:16:28,080
I had found the spell of the picture

733
01:16:28,250 --> 01:16:33,415
in an absolute life-likeliness
of expression.”

734
01:16:33,756 --> 01:16:35,462
Is that your book?

735
01:16:35,633 --> 01:16:37,624
No, I found it here.

736
01:16:43,808 --> 01:16:45,639
Can I have one?

737
01:16:54,777 --> 01:16:59,362
It’s our story:
a painter portraying his love.

738
01:17:00,074 --> 01:17:01,735
Shall I go on?

739
01:17:04,787 --> 01:17:08,996
“And in sooth
some who beheld the portrait

740
01:17:09,125 --> 01:17:12,959
spoke of its resemblance
in low words as of a mighty marvel,

741
01:17:13,129 --> 01:17:16,292
and a proof not less
of the power of the painter

742
01:17:16,465 --> 01:17:20,959
than of his deep love for her
whom he depicted so surpassingly well.

743
01:17:21,220 --> 01:17:25,463
But at length, as the labor drew
nearer to its conclusion,

744
01:17:25,641 --> 01:17:28,132
there were admitted none
into the turret.

745
01:17:28,310 --> 01:17:31,393
For the painter had grown wild
with the ardor of his work,

746
01:17:31,564 --> 01:17:37,025
and turned his eyes from the canvas
rarely, even to regard his wife.

747
01:17:37,319 --> 01:17:41,107
And he would not see that the tints
which he spread upon the canvas

748
01:17:41,282 --> 01:17:45,366
were drawn from the cheeks of her
who sat beside him.

749
01:17:45,828 --> 01:17:50,913
And when many weeks had passed,
and but little remained to do,

750
01:17:51,167 --> 01:17:55,126
save one brush upon the mouth
and one tint upon the eye,

751
01:17:55,296 --> 01:17:59,539
the spirit of the lady again flickered up
as the flame within a lamp.

752
01:18:00,009 --> 01:18:04,378
And then the brush was given,
and then the tint was placed.

753
01:18:05,097 --> 01:18:08,089
And, for one moment,
the painter stood entranced

754
01:18:08,267 --> 01:18:10,758
before the work he had wrought.

755
01:18:10,936 --> 01:18:14,099
But in the next, while he yet gazed,

756
01:18:14,273 --> 01:18:16,980
he grew tremulous and aghast,

757
01:18:17,109 --> 01:18:21,352
and crying with a loud voice,
“This is indeed Life itself!”

758
01:18:21,530 --> 01:18:24,863
turned suddenly to regard his beloved:

759
01:18:25,409 --> 01:18:27,024
She was dead!”

760
01:18:36,170 --> 01:18:38,536
I’d like to go to the Louvre.

761
01:18:38,881 --> 01:18:41,793
No, I don’t like looking at pictures.

762
01:18:45,095 --> 01:18:48,462
Why? Art and beauty are life!

763
01:18:52,228 --> 01:18:53,638
I adore you.

764
01:18:54,063 --> 01:18:55,428
And I love you.

765
01:19:03,697 --> 01:19:06,063
Why not come and live with me?

766
01:19:06,533 --> 01:19:08,899
Yes. I’ll tell Raoul it’s all over.

767
01:19:15,960 --> 01:19:20,203
Let me at least put my coat on
or I’ll catch cold!

768
01:19:20,339 --> 01:19:22,295
Stop acting hysterical.

769
01:19:29,682 --> 01:19:31,047
No, Raoul, not now!

770
01:19:31,225 --> 01:19:33,181
Stop acting hysterical!

771
01:19:33,644 --> 01:19:35,555
You know each other?

772
01:19:51,954 --> 01:19:53,945
What did I do wrong?

773
01:19:55,082 --> 01:19:57,164
You must take anyone who pays.

774
01:19:57,334 --> 01:20:00,872
Not anyone.
Sometimes it’s degrading.

775
01:20:01,672 --> 01:20:03,788
See? That’s where you’re wrong.

776
01:20:11,223 --> 01:20:15,466
The movies are a drag.
Weekdays we’re too busy,

777
01:20:15,644 --> 01:20:18,135
and on Sundays
there’s always a line.

778
01:20:21,233 --> 01:20:24,646
- Where are you going?
- Taking them back to their car.

779
01:20:24,820 --> 01:20:27,311
Why did you make me come?

780
01:20:27,865 --> 01:20:29,856
You’re going with them.

781
01:20:31,327 --> 01:20:34,319
HADES AND SONS

782
01:21:37,518 --> 01:21:39,349
Well, are you going?

783
01:21:54,827 --> 01:21:56,567
First the girl.

784
01:22:06,255 --> 01:22:07,745
First the money.

785
01:22:12,386 --> 01:22:14,217
Get the money.

786
01:22:47,296 --> 01:22:49,332
There’s 100,000 missing.

787
01:22:49,673 --> 01:22:51,254
Don’t move.

788
01:22:51,425 --> 01:22:53,711
Don’t think I won’t shoot
just because of the girl.

789
01:22:53,886 --> 01:22:55,672
No, don’t shoot me!

790
01:22:58,640 --> 01:23:01,427
You shoot.
I forgot to load.

